Yes, you can access the Pinecone.io Vector Database API through C#. Pinecone provides a RESTful API, which means you can communicate with it using any language that supports HTTP requests, including C#.

To access the Pinecone API in C#, you can use the `HttpClient` class, which is part of the .NET framework. Here's a basic example of how to make a GET request to retrieve a vector from the Pinecone API:
```csharp
using System;
using System.Net.Http;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using Newtonsoft.Json;

class PineconeClient
{
    private readonly string apiKey;

    public PineconeClient(string apiKey)
    {
        this.apiKey = apiKey;
    }

    public async Task<Vector> GetVectorAsync(string vectorId)
    {
        using var client = new HttpClient();
        client.DefaultRequestHeaders.Authorization = new System.Net.Http.Headers.AuthenticationHeaderValue("Bearer", apiKey);

        string url = $"https://api.pinecone.io/v1/vectors/{vectorId}";

        HttpResponseMessage response = await client.GetAsync(url);

        if (response.IsSuccessStatusCode)
        {
            string jsonResponse = await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync();
            Vector vector = JsonConvert.DeserializeObject<Vector>(jsonResponse);
            return vector;
        }
        else
        {
            throw new Exception($"Error: {response.StatusCode} - {response.ReasonPhrase}");
        }
    }
}

public class Vector
{
    public double[] Data { get; set; }
}
```
Replace the `apiKey` variable with your own Pinecone API key. This code defines a `PineconeClient` class that has a `GetVectorAsync` method, which takes a vector ID as a parameter and returns a `Vector` object.

